"Abstract A lawyer who uses a PC on her desk for word processing may believe that the computer is producing her documents. However, if a dictum of the Court of Appeal is followed she would be mistaken. According to the Court of Appeal the computer is merely a sophisticated quill pen or typewriter, and the documents are not produced by a computer. Graham Smith assesses the current state of play in the legal treatment of the continuing and thorny issue of so called ‘computer evidence’."
